article.description: Lauren Jackson scored 18 of her 22 points in the first half as the Seattle Storm routed the Phoenix Mercury 89-48 Friday night.
article.headline: Storm set records for victory margin (41), rebounds (49)
article.linkText: Storm set team records in 41-point rout of Mercury
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Lauren Jackson scored 18 of her 22 points in the
first half as the Seattle Storm routed Phoenix 89-48 on Friday
night for the Mercury's WNBA-record 17th consecutive road loss.

	   Phoenix, which has not won a road game since last July 27 at
Seattle, broke the mark of 16 straight road losses set by
Washington in the 1998 and 1999 seasons.

	   "It was our worst nightmare,'' Phoenix coach Linda Sharp said.
"We started out with a lead, and we were playing OK when all of
sudden Seattle stepped up.''

	   Seattle's Kamila Vodichkova added 14 points, and Amanda Lassiter
had 10 for the Storm (10-11).

	   Seattle's 41-point victory margin was a team record, besting its
26-point margin over Sacramento last month. The Storm also set a
team record with 49 rebounds, better than the 45 they grabbed last
summer against Washington.

	   "Hopefully we can take this momentum and carry it into the rest
of our games,'' Jackson said.

	   The Storm shot 51 percent from the floor in the first half,
erasing an early 9-2 deficit, and cruised to victory from there.

	   "At the 16-minute mark, I challenged them in the huddle,''
Storm coach Lin Dunn said. "Jackson took the team to a higher
level from there and we were able to get some quality minutes off
the bench.''

	   The Storm's Adia Barnes added eight points and had career highs
with nine rebounds and four assists.

	   Gordana Grubin scored 10 points for Phoenix (8-13) and
38-year-old Jennifer Gillom had seven. The Mercury have lost three
in a row.
